        <article class="text-gray-800 leading-7" id="content">
            <!-- Section 1: Introduction -->
            <section>
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">Why Java Still Matters in 2025</h2>
                <p>
                    “Java powers over 3 billion devices worldwide.” Oracle’s statement isn’t just a number—it’s a clear sign of how deeply Java shapes the systems we use every day. You’ve likely interacted with Java today without even realising it—whether through your bank’s app, an Android device, or the backend of a website you visited.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4">
                    Java isn’t just another programming language. It’s a foundation for creating applications that are secure, scalable, and work across platforms without rewriting code. That’s the magic of <strong>Write Once, Run Anywhere</strong>. And for professionals, that means one skillset opens doors to mobile app development, enterprise software, and even cloud-based systems.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4">
                    If you’re an IT student or developer aiming for career longevity, Java offers more than syntax—it builds a mindset for writing clean, modular, and reusable code. The language’s object-oriented structure is a valuable bridge to mastering others like Python, C#, and Kotlin. You’ll also gain access to a rich ecosystem of libraries and frameworks that speed up development and reduce complexity.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-4">
                    In this lesson, you’ll learn why Java has maintained its relevance for decades, what makes it different from other languages, and how you can start using it to solve real-world problems. Whether your goal is to land a software engineering role, build your own applications, or strengthen your problem-solving skills, Java is worth your time. Let’s explore why it continues to be one of the most trusted tools in the programming world!
                </p>
            </section>

