            <!-- Section 4: History of Java -->
            <section class="mt-8">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">History of Java</h2>
                <p>
                    Java was developed in the early 1990s by James Gosling and his team at Sun Microsystems, known as the <strong>Green Team</strong>. Originally intended for interactive television—like enabling live voting during a TV show—the technology was too advanced for the market at that time. Its breakthrough came when it was paired with the rapidly growing World Wide Web.
                </p>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-blue-600 mt-4 mb-2">Key Milestones</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
                    <li>Initially called <strong>Green Talk</strong>, then renamed <strong>Oak</strong> in 1994.</li>
                    <li>Official release as <strong>Java 1.0</strong> in 1995.</li>
                    <li>2006 – JVM made open source; J2SE renamed Java Standard Edition (Java SE).</li>
                    <li>Major releases: Java SE 6 (2006), Java SE 8 (2014). Java 8 and Java 11 are Long-Term Support (LTS) versions.</li>
                    <li>Since 2007, Java has been managed through the <strong>Java Community Process (JCP)</strong>.</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-4">
                    Today, Java powers frameworks and tools like JUnit, Eclipse, Hadoop, and Android. It’s used by companies such as Google, Accenture, Intel, and Philips. It’s also the official language for Android development, with its footprint extending into popular apps and games like PUBG.
                </p>
            </section>

